Users can create tables as large as they want inside of Confluence, but creating very large tables can cause slow page loads and even scripting errors with Firefox.

It would be nice if a table could be configured so that it would have "paginated" capabilities. The user could configure how many rows should be initially displayed in the table. The system would then determine how many rows existed and create a "Next Page", "End Page", "Previous Page", "First Page", "Skip to Page Number" type menu system that could be placed at the top (or bottom) of the table. The system then would only render the number of results configured to display in the table and update based on user clicks.

This would speed up page loads that had very large tables and could completely eliminate scripting errors that may be seen with Firefox.

